gical and theoretical reassessment of social science research, showing how it can function as a vehicle for activism and as a tool for marginalized people to theorize their lives. Tacking between personal narratives, ethnographic field notes, an original bilingual play about workers' rights, and examinations of anthropology as a discipline, the coauthors show how the participation of Mijangos García and López Juárez transformed the project's activist and academic dimensions. In so doing, they offer a guide for those wishing to expand the potential of ethnography to serve as a means for social transformation and decolonization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAnthropologyxMethodology. 0aCritical pedagogy. 0aDecolonization. 0aEducation and globalization. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspects. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aEurocentrism. 0aMarginality, SocialzDeveloping countries. 0aRacism in higher education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aLópez Juárez, Lucia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMijangos García, Mirian A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478004547zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478004547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478004547.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles